issue.title: Initiate panic at allocatting memory
issue.body:
### Describe the bug

I am a beginner with Wasmer. I have just created a new Docker container specifically to install Wasmer and attempted to use 'wasmer run test.wasm.' However, even in this simple scenario, it still throws an 'initiate panic' error.
So I suppose this might be a bug.

```sh
Ubuntu 22.04.3 LTS (GNU/Linux 5.15.0-79-generic x86_64)
:~$ docker -v
Docker version 24.0.5, build ced0996
wasmer run test.wasm
```
### Steps to reproduce
```sh
root@:/home# wasmer run filea5.wasm
⠋ Initializing the WebAssembly VM                                                                                       thread '<unnamed>' panicked at 'failed to set up alternative stack guard page: Cannot allocate memory (os error 12)', library/std/src/sys/unix/stack_overflow.rs:147:13
stack backtrace:
thread '<unnamed>' panicked at 'failed to set up alternative stack guard page: Cannot allocate memory (os error 12)', library/std/src/sys/unix/stack_overflow.rs:147:13
note: Some details are omitted, run with `RUST_BACKTRACE=full` for a verbose backtrace.
stack backtrace:
fatal runtime error: failed to initiate panic, error 5
Aborted
root@:/home# wasmer run filea5.wasm --singlepass
⠉ Initializing the WebAssembly VM                                                                                       thread 'main' panicked at 'called `Result::unwrap()` on an `Err` value: ThreadPoolBuildError { kind: IOError(Os { code: 11, kind: WouldBlock, message: "Resource temporarily unavailable" }) }', /home/runner/work/wasmer/wasmer/lib/wasix/src/runtime/task_manager/tokio.rs:69:22
⠙ Initializing the WebAssembly VM                                                                                       stack backtrace:
   0: rust_begin_unwind
             at /rustc/90c541806f23a127002de5b4038be731ba1458ca/library/std/src/panicking.rs:578:5
   1: core::panicking::panic_fmt
             at /rustc/90c541806f23a127002de5b4038be731ba1458ca/library/core/src/panicking.rs:67:14
   2: core::result::unwrap_failed
             at /rustc/90c541806f23a127002de5b4038be731ba1458ca/library/core/src/result.rs:1687:5
   3: wasmer_wasix::runtime::task_manager::tokio::TokioTaskManager::new
   4: wasmer_cli::commands::run::wasi::Wasi::prepare_runtime
   5: wasmer_cli::commands::run::Run::execute_inner
   6: wasmer_cli::commands::run::Run::execute
   7: wasmer_cli::cli::wasmer_main_inner
   8: wasmer_cli::cli::wasmer_main
note: Some details are omitted, run with `RUST_BACKTRACE=full` for a verbose backtrace.
⠂ Initializing the WebAssembly VM                                                                                       
root@:/home# rustc -V
rustc 1.73.0 (cc66ad468 2023-10-03)
```
My docker stats:
```
CPU %     MEM USAGE / LIMIT    MEM %     NET I/O          BLOCK I/O        PIDS
0.00%     6.578GiB / 1008GiB   0.65%     3.92GB / 102MB   187MB / 61.3GB   9673
```

issue.title: wasm receiving gibberish from typed host functions returning multivalue results
issue.body:
<!-- Thanks for the bug report! -->

### Describe the bug

I define import with `new_typed` for signature `fn() -> (i32, i32, i32, i32)`. On wasm side when I call this function, only first i32 is corrent, second one is actual third and other too is filled with random.

When I define import with `Function::new()`, all works as expected.

Code: https://github.com/Rulexec/wasmer-multivalue-demo/blob/5aeebc61bad481713aeaa08478d1bd59ccdc1ada/wasmer_host/src/main.rs

[Rust Explorer playground](https://www.rustexplorer.com/b#)

<!--
A clear and concise description of what the bug is.

Copy and paste the result of executing the following in your shell, so we can know the version of wasmer, Rust (if available) and architecture of your environment.
-->

```sh
$ wasmer -vV; rustc -vV
wasmer: command not found
rustc 1.72.0 (5680fa18f 2023-08-23)
binary: rustc
commit-hash: 5680fa18feaa87f3ff04063800aec256c3d4b4be
commit-date: 2023-08-23
host: x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu
release: 1.72.0
LLVM version: 16.0.5
```

<!-- A clear and concise description of what you expected to happen. -->
